# Fluent UI theming guidance

- Prefer Fluent UI components and their styling APIs (`FluentProvider`, Fluent UI theme tokens, component `styles`/`className`/`style` props) instead of adding custom “appearance” CSS.
- Avoid adding or modifying global/custom CSS files (e.g. `App.css`) for colors, backgrounds, typography, spacing, or hover/active states that duplicate Fluent UI behavior.
- If you need a visual change, implement it via Fluent UI theming (use the active theme/tokens) rather than hard-coded hex/rgb values.
- Exception: when generating “paper” artifacts for export (e.g. chart PNG/JPEG downloads), it is fine to use hard-coded export/background colors for readability/consistency; this should not affect on-screen UI theming.
- On-screen UI: avoid hard-coded color literals (`#...`, `rgb()`, `hsl()`, etc.) in TSX inline styles or CSS for visible surfaces. Use Fluent UI `theme`/`tokens` values and component `styles` instead.
- Ensure light and dark modes work natively:
  - Don’t assume a single theme (always use theme-driven tokens).
  - Don’t introduce CSS rules that prevent theme switching (e.g. fixed background/text colors without theme tokens).
- Avoid overriding Fluent UI component styles with custom CSS selectors or `!important`; prefer Fluent UI’s built-in theming/`styles` APIs.

# Quick examples
- Change a button look using Fluent UI’s `DefaultButton` + `styles` / theme tokens, not `button { background: ... }` in CSS.
- For page backgrounds, use Fluent UI theme tokens / layout components rather than a hard-coded `body { background: ... }`.

# Styling decision guardrails

- If the request is “make this Fluent UI component look different”: use Fluent UI’s styling props/APIs (and theme tokens); do not add/update global CSS (like `App.css`).
- If the request is “make the page/app look different”: change it via Fluent UI theme tokens or layout components; only use CSS for theme-neutral structure (no hard-coded colors).
- If Fluent UI doesn’t cover the exact need: ask what component/token to base it on, then implement via Fluent UI theming rather than raw appearance CSS.
- If you are considering editing any `*.css` file (including `src/App.css`):
  - Avoid theme-dependent appearance (colors, backgrounds, border/box-shadow colors, hover/active colors).
  - Prefer Fluent UI theming tokens / `styles` APIs and do not override Fluent UI component selectors.
  - Do not use `!important` to win against Fluent UI.
  - If CSS is unavoidable, restrict changes to theme-neutral structure (layout/spacing/positioning) only.

# Windows is Primary

While it's nice to be able to run on macOS and Linux, this app is primarily targeted for Windows. If there is a trade-off between naturalness on Windows vs another platform, prefer Windows.

This is meant to be a desktop app, so no concessions to the small screen need to be made.
